00:09:18,573 --> 00:09:20,241
We can't just wait.

248
00:09:20,325 --> 00:09:22,034
Everything'll come to a complete stop.

249
00:09:22,118 --> 00:09:23,911
What do you suggest, Maisel?

250
00:09:23,995 --> 00:09:26,372
Let's acquire the supply.

251
00:09:26,456 --> 00:09:28,041
What was that?

252
00:09:29,459 --> 00:09:31,669
We can't control our supply of chemicals

253
00:09:31,753 --> 00:09:33,671
if we can't control the supplier.

254
00:09:33,755 --> 00:09:35,965
So… let's become the supplier.

255
00:09:36,049 --> 00:09:38,426
And how would that work?
We buy Union Carbide?

256
00:09:38,510 --> 00:09:40,761
-[MAN CHUCKLES]
-We start small, Curtis.

257
00:09:40,845 --> 00:09:42,595
We acquire a local lab.

258
00:09:42,679 --> 00:09:44,973
We dig through universities for talent.

259
00:09:45,057 --> 00:09:47,142
We got a few of those in New York.

260
00:09:47,226 --> 00:09:47,512
A few.

261
00:09:47,596 --> 00:09:50,186
We hire our own
technicians, our own scientists.

262
00:09:50,270 --> 00:09:52,856
We build our own chain and
become our own suppliers.

263
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:54,482
They turn chemicals into plastic,

264
00:09:54,566 --> 00:09:56,818
and we turn plastic
into toys and coasters.

265
00:09:56,902 --> 00:10:00,029
Hell, let's make the chemicals, too.

266
00:10:00,113 --> 00:10:03,951
<i>Life</i> magazine says
conglomerates are the future.

267
00:10:05,327 --> 00:10:06,953
Francis, call Chase Manhattan.

268
00:10:07,037 --> 00:10:08,496
Let's take some baby steps.

269
00:10:08,580 --> 00:10:10,957
Set up a line of credit,
see what's out there.

270
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:13,375
And we need to call the West
Coast, give 'em a heads-up.

271
00:10:13,459 --> 00:10:14,960
-Curtis, give 'em a buzz.
-Will do, boss.

272
00:10:15,044 --> 00:10:16,545
We should send the CFO out there, too.

273
00:10:16,629 --> 00:10:18,172
As soon as possible.
Now, what else, guys?

274
00:10:18,256 --> 00:10:19,756
MAN: Just a couple of personnel things.

275
00:10:19,840 --> 00:10:22,551
IMOGENE: Can you believe
our babies are turning four?

276
00:10:22,635 --> 00:10:24,386
-They just turned three.
-They'll be in school

277
00:10:24,470 --> 00:10:25,804
before you know it, then college,

278
00:10:25,888 --> 00:10:27,431
then marriage, they'll have babies,

279
00:10:27,515 --> 00:10:29,349
become grandparents…
we'll be dead by then.

280
00:10:29,433 --> 00:10:31,018
-Yay.
-Sorry.

281
00:10:31,102 --> 00:10:33,145
Wait. You put marbles in here.
I'm doing marbles.

282
00:10:33,229 --> 00:10:35,063
-I thought you were doing gum.
-And you're putting

283
00:10:35,147 --> 00:10:36,815
Tiny Tina baby carriages
in the boys' bags.

284
00:10:36,899 --> 00:10:39,151
Oh, I told you, we should
get gender-specific bags.

285
00:10:39,235 --> 00:10:41,403
-Too much chatter.
-Sorry, Papa.

286
00:10:41,487 --> 00:10:44,530
-And what is all this?
-It's for Ethan's birthday party.

287
00:10:44,614 --> 00:10:47,158
-This is too much for him.
-This is for the kids

288
00:10:47,242 --> 00:10:49,285
-who come to the party.
-It's all their birthdays?

289
00:10:49,369 --> 00:10:51,387
If everyone gets a gift, it'll
keep the screaming down.

290
00:10:51,471 --> 00:10:51,621
So,

291
00:10:51,705 --> 00:10:53,623
everyone gets a gift,
everyone gets a compliment,

292
00:10:53,707 --> 00:10:55,917
everyone gets a hug… you're not preparing

293
00:10:56,001 --> 00:10:58,294
-these kids for the real world.
-Don't worry,

294
00:10:58,378 --> 00:11:00,296
we'll teach the kids how
cruel the world is next year,

295
00:11:00,380 --> 00:11:02,507
-when they're five.
-Did you need something, Mr. Weissman?

296
00:11:02,591 --> 00:11:04,884
