00:18:05,791 --> 00:18:08,793
Oh, hey, don't worry. I'll be back.

497
00:18:08,877 --> 00:18:12,005
Sophie, this is Susie
Myerson and Amanda Gleason.

498
00:18:12,089 --> 00:18:13,840
Amanda may be opening for you

499
00:18:13,924 --> 00:18:15,634
-in Jersey.
-Nice to meet you.

500
00:18:15,718 --> 00:18:17,510
-Ah, Sophie don't shake hands.
-Oh.

501
00:18:17,594 --> 00:18:20,180
-Sophie shakes bodies. Come here, you.
-Oh. Oh. [LAUGHING]

502
00:18:20,264 --> 00:18:22,599
[LAUGHS] Harry, make sure

503
00:18:22,683 --> 00:18:24,643
you cheat toward this
adorable young thing.

504
00:18:24,727 --> 00:18:26,561
-MIDGE: Oh. [CHUCKLES]
-I will.

505
00:18:26,645 --> 00:18:29,230
-So, you're gonna be the appetizer, huh?
-I'm hoping.

506
00:18:29,314 --> 00:18:31,066
Well, it's a tough gig.
They tell you that?

507
00:18:31,150 --> 00:18:33,485
-They did. I'm game.
-Good for you.

508
00:18:33,569 --> 00:18:35,236
Why don't you come over
to my house this week.

509
00:18:35,320 --> 00:18:37,237
I like to get to know my acolytes.

510
00:18:37,321 --> 00:18:38,489
I'm at your disposal.

511
00:18:38,573 --> 00:18:40,491
Harry, set it up.

512
00:18:40,575 --> 00:18:42,785
Look at those beauty-ful people.

513
00:18:42,869 --> 00:18:45,621
So long, all!

514
00:18:45,705 --> 00:18:47,414
Come here, my darlings.

515
00:18:47,498 --> 00:18:48,832
Susie, I'll be in touch.

516
00:18:48,916 --> 00:18:50,834
-Thanks, Harry.
-Okay.

517
00:18:50,918 --> 00:18:52,503
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

518
00:18:52,587 --> 00:18:54,505
SOPHIE: Oh! Where'd you get that hat?

519
00:18:56,924 --> 00:18:59,677
There's still lumps in there, Zelda.
They all have to go.

520
00:18:59,761 --> 00:19:01,762
-Yes, ma'am.
-It's not just about what he can chew.

521
00:19:01,846 --> 00:19:04,765
-Every lump is a choking hazard.
-Who's at risk of choking?

522
00:19:04,849 --> 00:19:07,183
Your father's bringing Mordecai
Glickman home for dinner.

523
00:19:07,267 --> 00:19:10,103
Professor Glickman?
He was an old man when I was a kid.

524
00:19:10,187 --> 00:19:12,522
-He still is.
-He had no liver when I was a kid.

525
00:19:12,606 --> 00:19:14,357
He still doesn't.

526
00:19:14,441 --> 00:19:16,275
-Too firm. Lose the peaches.
-Yes, ma'am.

527
00:19:16,359 --> 00:19:18,528
You're eating with us?
Please say you're eating with us.

528
00:19:18,612 --> 00:19:21,114
-I was planning on it.
-Your father especially wanted you

529
00:19:21,198 --> 00:19:22,782
to eat with us.

530
00:19:22,866 --> 00:19:24,784
-Too stringy. Lose the yams.
-Yes, ma'am.

531
00:19:24,868 --> 00:19:26,869
Grab some bowls. They'll want
to eat as soon as they come in,

532
00:19:26,953 --> 00:19:29,038
before Mordecai falls asleep.

533
00:19:29,122 --> 00:19:31,541
[SIGHS]

534
00:19:31,625 --> 00:19:33,001
So, remember,

535
00:19:33,085 --> 00:19:35,336
he's got 90% hearing
loss in his left ear,

536
00:19:35,420 --> 00:19:37,505
and his right ear is completely deaf.

537
00:19:37,589 --> 00:19:40,340
-So yell into his left ear.
-And sometimes he sees stars

538
00:19:40,424 --> 00:19:42,175
in front of his eyes and
he'll comment on them.

539
00:19:42,259 --> 00:19:43,844
He'll say, "Look at all
the pretty stars, everyone."

540
00:19:43,928 --> 00:19:46,013
-Just go along.
-We're all seeing pretty stars.

541
00:19:46,097 --> 00:19:46,189
Mm.

542
00:19:46,273 --> 00:19:48,598
Is it okay if I seat Professor
Glickman here, ma'am?

543
00:19:48,682 --> 00:19:50,934
Oh, he shouldn't sit there.
If he falls, he'll hit his head

544
00:19:51,018 --> 00:19:52,769
-on the mirror.
-But if he falls over there,

545
00:19:52,853 --> 00:19:54,771
he'll hit his head on
the drink cart. [SIGHS]

546
00:19:54,855 --> 00:19:57,274
I should have had Abe tell me
which way he was tilting today.

547
00:19:57,358 --> 00:19:58,525
Have some pillows handy.

548
00:19:58,609 --> 00:20:00,610
-[DOOR OPENS]
-ABE: Hello!

549
00:20:00,694 --> 00:20:02,696
We're here!

550
00:20:05,407 --> 00:20:06,324
Abe?

551
00:20:06,408 --> 00:20:08,994
Rose, this is David Blumenthal.

552
00:20:09,078 --> 00:20:10,995
David, this is my wife, Rose.

553
00:20:11,079 --> 00:20:12,496
Nice to meet you, Mrs. Weissman.

554
00:20:12,580 --> 00:20:14,832
-Likewise.
-And this is my daughter,

555
00:20:14,916 --> 00:20:17,543
-Miriam.
-Very nice to meet you, Miriam.

556
00:20:17,627 --> 00:20:20,087
Nice to meet you, too, Mr. Blumenthal.

557
00:20:20,171 --> 00:20:21,338
Please, call me David.

558
00:20:21,422 --> 00:20:23,674
David.

559
00:20:23,758 --> 00:20:26,093
Zelda, why don't you
take Mr. Blumenthal's coat.

560
00:20:26,177 --> 00:20:27,178
Yes, ma'am.

561
00:20:28,805 --> 00:20:30,723
[QUIETLY]: This is not
Professor Glickman.

562
00:20:30,807 --> 00:20:32,183
-Of course it isn't.
-I thought

563
00:20:32,267 --> 00:20:33,893
you were bringing home
Professor Glickman.

564
00:20:33,977 --> 00:20:35,811
I said a "colleague,"
not "Professor Glickman."

565
00:20:35,895 --> 00:20:37,480
David, please join us in the living room.

566
00:20:37,564 --> 00:20:39,315
We can chat a bit before dinner.

567
00:20:39,399 --> 00:20:43,318
Mmm, this looks… charmingly eclectic.

568
00:20:43,402 --> 00:20:44,819
Is this dinner, Rose?

569
00:20:44,903 --> 00:20:46,571
It's dinner for Mordecai Glickman.

570
00:20:46,655 --> 00:20:48,990
I wasn't aware you were
bringing home someone with teeth.

571
00:20:49,074 --> 00:20:51,159
-[CHUCKLES]
-[CHUCKLES] Well, David,

572
00:20:51,243 --> 00:20:52,410
would you like a drink?

573
00:20:52,494 --> 00:20:54,829
We have… peppermint schnapps.

574
00:20:54,913 --> 00:20:57,248
Rose, why is there just
peppermint schnapps?

575
00:20:57,332 --> 00:20:58,875
It's what Professor Glickman drinks.

576
00:20:58,959 --> 00:21:00,502
I have scotch somewhere.

577
00:21:00,586 --> 00:21:02,670
I'm fine, thank you.
I don't need a drink.

578
00:21:02,754 --> 00:21:05,173
I hope you like applesauce
and peach slices, Mr. Blumenthal.

579
00:21:05,257 --> 00:21:07,217
-I like whatever you're serving.
-Good, because that's what

580
00:21:07,301 --> 00:21:10,136
we're serving: applesauce and
peach slices and mashed potatoes

581
00:21:10,220 --> 00:21:12,554
and consommé and hard-boiled
eggs and pureed cauliflower

582
00:21:12,638 --> 00:21:14,098
and pudding for dessert.

583
00:21:14,182 --> 00:21:15,516
Your teeth will wonder
what they're there for.

584
00:21:15,600 --> 00:21:17,518
Miriam, will you help
me in the kitchen, please?

585
00:21:17,602 --> 00:21:19,186
Mm.

586
00:21:19,270 --> 00:21:21,939
Excuse me.

587
00:21:23,566 --> 00:21:27,028
So, David, which part of
Westchester are you from?

588
00:21:28,321 --> 00:21:30,114
What do we have that's real food?

589
00:21:30,198 --> 00:21:32,199
-I have steaks, but they're frozen.
-This is a nightmare.

590
00:21:32,283 --> 00:21:33,867
-The nerve of him.
-The nerve of him.

591
00:21:33,951 --> 00:21:35,369
You said he was bringing
home Professor Glickman.

592
00:21:35,453 --> 00:21:36,703
I said he was bringing home a colleague,

593
00:21:36,787 --> 00:21:38,288
and it's always Professor Glickman.

594
00:21:38,372 --> 00:21:39,957
-Is this a set-up?
-Of course it's a set-up.

595
00:21:40,041 --> 00:21:41,959
Why is he doing this?
Why is he trying to set me up

596
00:21:42,043 --> 00:21:42,465
with some guy?

597
00:21:42,549 --> 00:21:44,210
Your father's nothing
but a common souteneur.

598
00:21:44,294 --> 00:21:46,212
-A what?
-A pimp. Your father's a pimp.

599
00:21:46,296 --> 00:21:46,921
He's not a pimp.

600
00:21:47,005 --> 00:21:48,881
He's trying to breed
you, like a prize mare.

601
00:21:48,965 --> 00:21:50,633
Just the presumption of what he's doing.

602
00:21:50,717 --> 00:21:52,718
-I'm so mad.
-And this man is not even attractive.

603
00:21:52,802 --> 00:21:54,303
Well, he's not unattractive.

604
00:21:54,387 --> 00:21:55,888
Oh, Miriam, you are not
going out with this man.

605
00:21:55,972 --> 00:21:57,348
Of course I'm not
going out with this man.

606
00:21:57,432 --> 00:21:58,891
But you said he was attractive.

607
00:21:58,975 --> 00:22:00,101
-[ARGUING CONTINUES]
-I had a car for a while.

608
00:22:00,185 --> 00:22:01,602
A '55 Bel Air.

609
00:22:01,686 --> 00:22:03,354
But the upkeep was enormous,

610
00:22:03,438 --> 00:22:05,773
and parking in the city's murder, so…

611
00:22:05,857 --> 00:22:08,276
Yes, well, parking and upkeep is…

612
00:22:08,360 --> 00:22:10,532
ROSE: So you would encourage
your father to be a pimp?

613
00:22:10,616 --> 00:22:10,862
Look,

614
00:22:10,946 --> 00:22:12,071
he's a lot of things, but I don't think

615
00:22:12,155 --> 00:22:13,322
it's fair to call him a pimp.

616
00:22:13,406 --> 00:22:14,323
ROSE: Well, he's being a pimp.

617
00:22:14,407 --> 00:22:16,324
Upkeep is pretty onerous.

618
00:22:16,408 --> 00:22:18,660
David, will you excuse me a moment?

619
00:22:18,744 --> 00:22:20,787
The girls sound a little… excited.

620
00:22:20,871 --> 00:22:22,330
-Of course.
-ROSE: So it's my fault?

621
00:22:22,414 --> 00:22:24,666
MIDGE: I should have
eaten at the Automat tonight.

622
00:22:24,750 --> 00:22:26,637
-That's what I think.
-Miriam, stop it.

623
00:22:26,721 --> 00:22:27,669
What is going on?

624
00:22:27,753 --> 00:22:30,046
-We can hear every word you're saying.
-Abe Weissman,

625
00:22:30,130 --> 00:22:32,424
what made you think you could
just bring a man home like this?

626
00:22:32,508 --> 00:22:34,885
He's a colleague.
I bring colleagues home for dinner.

627
00:22:34,969 --> 00:22:36,720
-He's not just a colleague.
-You brought him home

628
00:22:36,804 --> 00:22:39,139
-to set him up with Miriam.
-I did no such thing.

629
00:22:39,223 --> 00:22:39,651
Come on.

630
00:22:39,735 --> 00:22:42,350
David Blumenthal is a
colleague at my school.

631
00:22:42,434 --> 00:22:44,186
-Is he a bachelor?
-I think so.

632
00:22:44,270 --> 00:22:44,607
Oh, Abe!

633
00:22:44,691 --> 00:22:46,937
What, I can only bring
home married colleagues?

634
00:22:47,021 --> 00:22:48,689
-Mm.
-Come on, you never bring anyone home,

635
00:22:48,773 --> 00:22:50,941
and tonight you show up
with this attractive young guy?

636
00:22:51,025 --> 00:22:53,027
-Semi-attractive.
-He's not unattractive.

637
00:22:53,111 --> 00:22:55,446
-Which side are you on here?
-His looks have nothing to do

638
00:22:55,530 --> 00:22:58,449
with this. Now, please, can
we get dinner on the table?

639
00:22:58,533 --> 00:22:59,533
Dinner's a disaster.

640
00:22:59,617 --> 00:23:01,535
He says he's not picky.

641
00:23:01,619 --> 00:23:04,121
Oh, and Mordecai
Glickman is no longer with us.

642
00:23:04,205 --> 00:23:04,736
Since when?

643
00:23:04,820 --> 00:23:07,124
Since we went to his
funeral four years ago.

644
00:23:07,208 --> 00:23:08,292
That's right. It was the liveliest

645
00:23:08,376 --> 00:23:09,627
I'd seen Mordecai in years.

646
00:23:09,711 --> 00:23:11,713
Dinner, please.

647
00:23:13,047 --> 00:23:14,798
You think he's telling the truth?

648
00:23:14,882 --> 00:23:17,302
I don't know anything anymore.

649
00:23:19,303 --> 00:23:21,137
[MIDGE SIGHS]

650
00:23:21,221 --> 00:23:22,555
Thursday is soft foods night

651
00:23:22,639 --> 00:23:24,140
here at the Weissman home, David.

652
00:23:24,224 --> 00:23:25,225
I hope you don't mind.

653
00:23:25,309 --> 00:23:26,726
I'm anything but picky, Abe.

654
00:23:26,810 --> 00:23:29,479
-[CHUCKLES]
-Please, everybody, sit.

655
00:23:29,563 --> 00:23:31,565
[CLEARS THROAT]

656
00:23:37,738 --> 00:23:41,575
So, David here is a divorce lawyer.

657
00:23:45,287 --> 00:23:48,498
David, can I dish you
up some peach slices?

658
00:23:48,582 --> 00:23:50,874
-You said he was a colleague.
-I do teach law part-time.

659
00:23:50,958 --> 00:23:53,085
-Shut up, David.
-She needs an attorney.

660
00:23:53,169 --> 00:23:54,670
-She does not need an attorney.
-Maybe I should go.

661
00:23:54,754 --> 00:23:56,505
Papa, this was not the time or the place.

662
00:23:56,589 --> 00:23:58,257
Mr. Blumenthal, I'm afraid
my husband brought you here

663
00:23:58,341 --> 00:23:59,591
under false pretenses.

664
00:23:59,675 --> 00:24:01,718
An informative colloquy can't hurt.

665
00:24:01,802 --> 00:24:02,928
I can just leave my card with you.

666
00:24:03,012 --> 00:24:04,054
She doesn't need your card.

667
00:24:04,138 --> 00:24:05,055
Papa, can we

668
00:24:05,139 --> 00:24:06,598
colloquy in your study, please?

669
00:24:06,682 --> 00:24:07,599
The food will get cold.

670
00:24:07,683 --> 00:24:08,850
It's already cold.

671
00:24:08,934 --> 00:24:10,894
-David, excuse us.
-I understand.

672
00:24:10,978 --> 00:24:12,729
No, there's nothing for you
to understand, Mr. Blumenthal.

673
00:24:12,813 --> 00:24:15,649
-Mm-mm.
-Rose, please, my study.

674
00:24:19,653 --> 00:24:22,781
Don't you dare pull paperwork
out of that briefcase of yours.

675
00:24:24,783 --> 00:24:27,868
Papa, you should have
told me you were doing this.

676
00:24:27,952 --> 00:24:31,205
We should not be in denial
about what's happening here.

677
00:24:31,289 --> 00:24:32,790
Who are you to say that?

678
00:24:32,874 --> 00:24:34,458
-I'm her father.
-For now.

679
00:24:34,542 --> 00:24:36,210
What does that even mean?

680
00:24:36,294 --> 00:24:38,713
And why would you think I
would bring someone home

681
00:24:38,797 --> 00:24:41,007
-to set you up with?
-Because you're a common souteneur.

682
00:24:41,091 --> 00:24:43,384
-A what?
-A pimp. Papa, you're a pimp.

683
00:24:43,468 --> 00:24:45,052
I beg your pardon.

684
00:24:45,136 --> 00:24:46,804
-Sounds better in French.
-I wouldn't set you up

685
00:24:46,888 --> 00:24:48,514
with anyone. I don't even know your type.

686
00:24:48,598 --> 00:24:51,267
-Joel's her type.
-Miriam doesn't have a type.

687
00:24:51,351 --> 00:24:52,934
My God, before Joel,

688
00:24:53,018 --> 00:24:55,020
you were with that ultra
white Palmer Witherspoon.

689
00:24:55,104 --> 00:24:56,730
Oh, that name you remember?

690
00:24:56,814 --> 00:24:58,690
He was like a pole-vaulter
from Triumph of the Will.

691
00:24:58,774 --> 00:25:01,818
Papa, this is my concern, not yours.

692
00:25:01,902 --> 00:25:03,361
You're my daughter.

693
00:25:03,445 --> 00:25:04,863
Your concerns are my concerns.

694
00:25:04,947 --> 00:25:07,073
Miriam and Joel are not divorcing.

695
00:25:07,157 --> 00:25:10,910
Rose, we need to talk about this.

696
00:25:10,994 --> 00:25:13,830
They live apart. She has a job.

697
00:25:13,914 --> 00:25:15,540
He moved in with that girl.

698
00:25:15,624 --> 00:25:18,710
No one at Ethan's party
has been told the same thing.

699
00:25:18,794 --> 00:25:21,421
It'll be 20 adults all
sitting six feet apart

700
00:25:21,505 --> 00:25:23,173
so they can't compare stories

701
00:25:23,257 --> 00:25:26,342
with Dody running interference.

702
00:25:26,426 --> 00:25:28,010
[SIGHS]

703
00:25:28,094 --> 00:25:30,012
Things need to move on.

704
00:25:30,096 --> 00:25:32,139
Miriam needs to be settled.

705
00:25:32,223 --> 00:25:35,684
And that means they need to divorce.

706
00:25:35,768 --> 00:25:37,561
I don't want to talk about this anymore.

707
00:25:37,645 --> 00:25:39,897
Now I'm gonna go to the
kitchen and grab some celery

708
00:25:39,981 --> 00:25:42,400
because we all need
something fibrous to eat.

709
00:25:44,402 --> 00:25:46,987
[DOOR CLOSES]

710
00:25:47,071 --> 00:25:49,323
Her name's Imogene.

711
00:25:57,038 --> 00:25:59,040
♪♪

712
00:26:05,255 --> 00:26:08,257
<i>♪ Now… ♪</i>

713
00:26:08,341 --> 00:26:11,845
<i>♪ You say you're lonely ♪</i>

714
00:26:13,513 --> 00:26:17,308
<i>♪ You cry the long night through ♪</i>

715
00:26:17,392 --> 00:26:19,352
I guess it's time.

716
00:26:19,436 --> 00:26:23,106
<i>♪ Well, you can cry me a river ♪</i>

717
00:26:24,774 --> 00:26:28,902
<i>♪ Cry me a river ♪</i>

718
00:26:28,986 --> 00:26:32,114
<i>♪ I cried a river ♪</i>

719
00:26:32,198 --> 00:26:34,450
<i>♪ Over you ♪</i>

720
00:26:36,869 --> 00:26:39,037
Rose.

721
00:26:39,121 --> 00:26:40,997
[SIGHS] Rose.

722
00:26:41,081 --> 00:26:42,416
Privacy, please.

723
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:43,834
We need to talk.

724
00:26:43,918 --> 00:26:45,794
You bring that man home.

725
00:26:45,878 --> 00:26:47,587
A lawyer.

726
00:26:47,671 --> 00:26:49,840
I could strangle you.

727
00:26:49,924 --> 00:26:51,383
I want to tell you something.

728
00:26:51,467 --> 00:26:53,718
Well, tell it to your colleague.

729
00:26:53,802 --> 00:26:56,722
You need to know… Rose!

730
00:27:01,559 --> 00:27:03,936
You need to know about Miriam and Joel.

731
00:27:04,020 --> 00:27:05,980
What about them?

732
00:27:06,064 --> 00:27:10,276
Joel is not going to come back.

733
00:27:10,360 --> 00:27:11,694
How do you know?

734
00:27:11,778 --> 00:27:15,906
Because he already did… come back.

735
00:27:15,990 --> 00:27:18,576
And she turned him away.

736
00:27:18,660 --> 00:27:20,411
"She" who?

737
00:27:20,495 --> 00:27:21,662
Miriam.

738
00:27:21,746 --> 00:27:23,038
-Our Miriam?
-Yes.

739
00:27:23,122 --> 00:27:24,415
I don't understand.

740
00:27:27,961 --> 00:27:31,087
About a month ago, Joel came here

741
00:27:31,171 --> 00:27:34,716
and he asked to come back.

742
00:27:34,800 --> 00:27:36,801
She said no.

743
00:27:36,885 --> 00:27:41,181
-She said no.
-She said no.

744
00:27:45,310 --> 00:27:47,187
And you didn't tell me.

745
00:27:47,271 --> 00:27:49,230
I didn't know how.

746
00:27:49,314 --> 00:27:51,232
And she didn't tell me.

747
00:27:51,316 --> 00:27:53,569
She probably didn't know how.

748
00:27:55,612 --> 00:27:57,906
Well, thank you very much.

749
00:28:01,200 --> 00:28:03,494
Drina! I need the ball.

750
00:28:03,578 --> 00:28:05,120
And the cards.

751
00:28:05,204 --> 00:28:07,623
I need the ball and the
cards and two cups of tea.

752
00:28:07,707 --> 00:28:10,585
-WOMAN: Hello.
-Drina?

753
00:28:12,503 --> 00:28:14,838
Welcome. Please, have a seat.

754
00:28:14,922 --> 00:28:16,089
Who are you?

755
00:28:16,173 --> 00:28:18,133
I am Madame Cosma.

756
00:28:18,217 --> 00:28:20,135
I see your future so you don't have to.

757
00:28:20,219 --> 00:28:22,221
N… No. What happened to Drina?

758
00:28:22,305 --> 00:28:24,932
Drina, she's home now.

759
00:28:25,016 --> 00:28:27,100
Drina went back to the old
country without telling me?

760
00:28:27,184 --> 00:28:29,603
The old country, she's from the Bronx.

761
00:28:29,687 --> 00:28:30,896
Oh, no, no, no.
Drina's from Eastern Europe.

762
00:28:30,980 --> 00:28:33,397
A small city just outside Bucharest.

763
00:28:33,481 --> 00:28:35,441
Okay.

764
00:28:35,525 --> 00:28:37,109
I need to see her. She tells my fortune.

765
00:28:37,193 --> 00:28:39,320
She reads my tea leaves.
She helps guide my life.

766
00:28:39,404 --> 00:28:41,781
Well, now I am the
person who's gonna do that,

767
00:28:41,865 --> 00:28:43,324
but between you and me,

768
00:28:43,408 --> 00:28:45,993
the tea leaf thing, kind of a scam.

769
00:28:46,077 --> 00:28:49,372
Pyromancy. Gazing into fire…

770
00:28:49,456 --> 00:28:51,791
Much more accurate, prettier, too.

771
00:28:51,875 --> 00:28:54,835
-This isn't happening.
-The price is the same.

772
00:28:54,919 --> 00:28:57,713
And if you pay in advance,
your tenth visit is free.

773
00:28:57,797 --> 00:28:59,340
Plus, I throw in a charm.

774
00:28:59,424 --> 00:29:01,842
I don't believe this. What am I gonna do?

775
00:29:01,926 --> 00:29:06,012
I don't even have to
consult the cards to see

776
00:29:06,096 --> 00:29:09,683
that it's all going wrong for you.

777
00:29:12,269 --> 00:29:15,397
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

778
00:29:29,662 --> 00:29:31,205
Hello, Abe.

779
00:29:32,831 --> 00:29:36,083
Abe. Abe!

780
00:29:36,167 --> 00:29:39,295
I just need a moment, please.

781
00:29:39,379 --> 00:29:41,297
Okay, I know you hate me.

782
00:29:41,381 --> 00:29:42,840
I don't blame you.

783
00:29:42,924 --> 00:29:44,967
I'm not feeling too hot
about myself, either.

784
00:29:45,051 --> 00:29:47,970
I just wanted to talk to you
about what my father said

785
00:29:48,054 --> 00:29:51,515
at that dinner a couple months ago.

786
00:29:51,599 --> 00:29:53,225
For Professor Weissman?

787
00:29:53,309 --> 00:29:55,644
I'll take it.

788
00:29:55,728 --> 00:29:57,980
Abe, you got a package.

789
00:30:03,653 --> 00:30:06,113
Okay, then I'll talk to your door.

790
00:30:06,197 --> 00:30:08,197
It's true what he said.

791
00:30:08,281 --> 00:30:10,199
Miriam and I were broke.

792
00:30:10,283 --> 00:30:11,576
I mean, flat broke.

793
00:30:11,660 --> 00:30:12,952
We were spending more than we made,

794
00:30:13,036 --> 00:30:14,871
couldn't save anything.

795
00:30:14,955 --> 00:30:17,332
But she had no idea
that that was the case.

796
00:30:17,416 --> 00:30:20,335
She'd ask about money and
I'd say we're fine, we're good.

797
00:30:20,419 --> 00:30:22,879
She trusted me.

798
00:30:22,963 --> 00:30:25,673
She's always trusted me.

799
00:30:25,757 --> 00:30:28,176
There's a lot of things I
can't make right again,

800
00:30:28,260 --> 00:30:30,679
but there's some things I can.

801
00:30:34,683 --> 00:30:37,018
Thanks.

802
00:30:38,477 --> 00:30:40,563
Table.

803
00:30:42,231 --> 00:30:44,566
I've been stepping up at work, Abe.

804
00:30:44,650 --> 00:30:47,069
And I'm in line for a new job.

805
00:30:47,153 --> 00:30:48,695
It's a pretty big promotion.

806
00:30:48,779 --> 00:30:51,531
Well, good for you.

807
00:30:51,615 --> 00:30:57,204
I'm not bragging, it just means… Look.

808
00:30:57,288 --> 00:31:00,666
It comes with a raise, a pretty big one.

809
00:31:00,750 --> 00:31:02,668
And I've been crunching the numbers.

810
00:31:02,752 --> 00:31:04,419
Uh-huh.

811
00:31:04,503 --> 00:31:06,797
Miriam and the kids can't
live at your place forever.

812
00:31:06,881 --> 00:31:09,715
They're gonna need their own
place, three bedrooms at least.

813
00:31:09,799 --> 00:31:11,300
I can swing that now.

814
00:31:11,384 --> 00:31:12,927
And she wants the kids
to go to private school?

815
00:31:13,011 --> 00:31:14,345
Yes, she does.

816
00:31:14,429 --> 00:31:16,305
Ethan to Collegiate
and Esther to Brearley.

817
00:31:16,389 --> 00:31:19,350
Tuition's about $1,100 each,
and I budgeted for that, too.

818
00:31:19,434 --> 00:31:22,019
Then there's clothes, entertainment.

819
00:31:22,103 --> 00:31:23,854
I want them to go to shows and movies,

820
00:31:23,938 --> 00:31:26,440
take piano lessons, go on vacations.

821
00:31:26,524 --> 00:31:27,858
It's all here.

822
00:31:27,942 --> 00:31:29,860
Everything they need is accounted for.

823
00:31:29,944 --> 00:31:31,987
And my new salary will cover it all.

824
00:31:32,071 --> 00:31:34,865
And if you don't get the new job?

825
00:31:34,949 --> 00:31:37,410
Then I'll go back to
working for my father.

826
00:31:37,494 --> 00:31:39,995
Either way, that is the salary.

827
00:31:40,079 --> 00:31:43,998
Joel, you know that I
am pretty good at math.

828
00:31:44,082 --> 00:31:45,792
-Right?
-Yes.

829
00:31:45,876 --> 00:31:48,169
There's nothing left for you.

830
00:31:48,253 --> 00:31:49,963
I'll be fine.

831
00:31:50,047 --> 00:31:52,257
-You'll be fine?
-The new job takes me

832
00:31:52,341 --> 00:31:53,633
to the West Coast a lot,

833
00:31:53,717 --> 00:31:54,926
eventually, I'll be moving there.

834
00:31:55,010 --> 00:31:56,177
To California?

835
00:31:56,261 --> 00:31:57,554
Miriam said you hate California.

836
00:31:57,638 --> 00:31:59,431
Doesn't matter.

837
00:31:59,515 --> 00:32:01,933
But what about the kids?

838
00:32:02,017 --> 00:32:04,269
They're taken care of.
Anything they want.

839
00:32:04,353 --> 00:32:06,062
But you won't see them.

840
00:32:06,146 --> 00:32:08,774
They don't need me.

841
00:32:12,027 --> 00:32:13,152
Joel.

842
00:32:13,236 --> 00:32:15,404
So do me a favor, Abe?

843
00:32:15,488 --> 00:32:17,406
Be the go-between on this.

844
00:32:17,490 --> 00:32:19,690
Tell Midge that she
and the kids are all set.

845
00:32:21,452 --> 00:32:23,162
You'll do that?

846
00:32:23,246 --> 00:32:25,456
I'll do that.

847
00:32:26,958 --> 00:32:29,418
This is good, Abe.

848
00:32:29,502 --> 00:32:31,211
You should be happy.

849
00:32:31,295 --> 00:32:33,672
Okay.

850
00:32:33,756 --> 00:32:36,425
I'll be happy.

851
00:32:44,391 --> 00:32:46,393
[CAR HORN HONKS IN DISTANCE]

852
00:32:50,897 --> 00:32:52,899
[GRAND MUSICAL TONES PLAY]

853
00:32:56,903 --> 00:32:58,321
Good afternoon.

854
00:32:58,405 --> 00:32:59,739
Miss Gleason, I presume.

855
00:32:59,823 --> 00:33:01,783
Yes. Good afternoon.

856
00:33:01,867 --> 00:33:03,075
Miss Lennon is expecting you.

857
00:33:03,159 --> 00:33:04,577
Please come in.

858
00:33:04,661 --> 00:33:07,163
Thank you.

859
00:33:10,584 --> 00:33:13,336
So who composed that doorbell? Puccini?

860
00:33:13,420 --> 00:33:14,796
I wouldn't know.

861
00:33:14,880 --> 00:33:17,672
Probably just some guy
at the doorbell factory.

862
00:33:17,756 --> 00:33:19,591
Your coat, miss?

863
00:33:19,675 --> 00:33:21,593
Oh, yes.

864
00:33:21,677 --> 00:33:24,179
Wow. Such a big foyer.

865
00:33:24,263 --> 00:33:25,889
You should put in a Ping-Pong table.

866
00:33:25,973 --> 00:33:28,099
-Jenkins?
-Oh.

867
00:33:28,183 --> 00:33:31,186
-Oh, hi, Jenkins.
-The lady's coat.

868
00:33:40,195 --> 00:33:42,155
They look like they could use some water.

869
00:33:42,239 --> 00:33:44,157
Miss Lennon will be down shortly.

870
00:33:44,241 --> 00:33:46,742
SOPHIE: Miss Lennon is down now.

871
00:33:46,826 --> 00:33:48,828
[CHUCKLES]

872
00:33:50,705 --> 00:33:53,040
Sophie. Hi.

873
00:33:53,124 --> 00:33:55,000
[CHUCKLING] So good to see you.

874
00:33:55,084 --> 00:33:56,919
Oh, and you're on time.

875
00:33:57,003 --> 00:33:58,754
That's so unlike a comic.

876
00:33:58,838 --> 00:34:00,506
-I tend to be punctual.
-Mmm.

877
00:34:00,590 --> 00:34:03,592
The lady was inquiring as to
the provenance of the doorbell.

878
00:34:03,676 --> 00:34:05,553
It was a joke. I said Puccini.

879
00:34:05,637 --> 00:34:06,971
It was Aaron Copland.

880
00:34:07,055 --> 00:34:09,056
Wait. Aaron Copland wrote your doorbell?

881
00:34:09,140 --> 00:34:10,558
It's something he does.

882
00:34:10,642 --> 00:34:13,143
Aaron writes doorbells
for all his friends.

883
00:34:13,227 --> 00:34:16,730
I guess even composers
need to let loose sometimes.

884
00:34:16,814 --> 00:34:18,439
Dawes, how is the light
in the Blue Room today?

885
00:34:18,523 --> 00:34:20,024
I got a terrible night's sleep,

886
00:34:20,108 --> 00:34:22,402
and you know that makes
my eyes sensitive to light.

887
00:34:22,486 --> 00:34:24,863
Is the light caustic today?

888
00:34:24,947 --> 00:34:26,907
I'll check, ma'am.

889
00:34:39,711 --> 00:34:42,463
The light is not caustic, ma'am.

890
00:34:42,547 --> 00:34:44,591
The Blue Room it is.

891
00:34:54,100 --> 00:34:56,602
Wow. Wow.

892
00:34:56,686 --> 00:34:59,187
I had to fire six
designers to get it here.

893
00:34:59,271 --> 00:35:00,898
I'm not sure it was worth it.

894
00:35:00,982 --> 00:35:03,317
-This is gorgeous.
-Don't touch.

895
00:35:03,401 --> 00:35:05,027
That was Cole Porter's.

896
00:35:05,111 --> 00:35:09,031
He wrote "Begin the Beguine"
on that very instrument.

897
00:35:09,115 --> 00:35:11,283
And this rug was once
owned by George Gershwin.

898
00:35:11,367 --> 00:35:12,826
Should I walk on it?

899
00:35:12,910 --> 00:35:15,871
Lightly.
You'll have the grand tour after we eat.

900
00:35:15,955 --> 00:35:18,373
Terrific. I'd love to see the kitchen.

901
00:35:18,457 --> 00:35:20,125
The kitchen? Really?

902
00:35:20,209 --> 00:35:21,667
Why?

903
00:35:21,751 --> 00:35:23,419
Because I love kitchens.

904
00:35:23,503 --> 00:35:25,630
Really? Kitchens?

905
00:35:25,714 --> 00:35:27,257
Why?

906
00:35:28,508 --> 00:35:30,217
-They're neat.
-To be honest,

907
00:35:30,301 --> 00:35:32,678
I haven't been in our
kitchen in quite some time.

908
00:35:32,762 --> 00:35:35,765
I'm on the road, I'm upstairs,

909
00:35:35,849 --> 00:35:38,225
but if it means that
much to you, we'll find it.

910
00:35:38,309 --> 00:35:40,394
Ready for tea, ma'am?

911
00:35:40,478 --> 00:35:42,605
Yes, Dawes. Let's sit.

912
00:35:46,317 --> 00:35:49,320
So the bread for the finger
sandwiches is from Provence.

913
00:35:49,404 --> 00:35:51,530
Uh, the macaroons are French, too.

914
00:35:51,614 --> 00:35:55,533
Clotted cream is from London,
of course, and the scones.

915
00:35:55,617 --> 00:35:57,953
I would never eat a domestic scone.

916
00:35:58,037 --> 00:35:59,704
Shall we prepare your plate, miss?

917
00:35:59,788 --> 00:36:01,373
Yes, thank you.

918
00:36:01,457 --> 00:36:04,584
And I will have my usual, Dawes.

919
00:36:04,668 --> 00:36:07,712
So… this is you.

920
00:36:07,796 --> 00:36:09,005
This is me.

921
00:36:09,089 --> 00:36:11,049
-Surprised?
-A little.

922
00:36:11,133 --> 00:36:13,593
You were expecting
Sophie Lennon, weren't ya?

923
00:36:13,677 --> 00:36:13,873
Yes.

924
00:36:13,957 --> 00:36:16,930
[CHUCKLES] It's a very
successful charade, isn't it?

925
00:36:17,014 --> 00:36:20,058
-Amazing.
-It's all fat suit and makeup.

926
00:36:20,142 --> 00:36:21,685
How do people not know?

927
00:36:21,769 --> 00:36:24,311
I've never seen a picture
of you out of character.

928
00:36:24,395 --> 00:36:26,271
I pay the publicists, I pay the rags.

929
00:36:26,355 --> 00:36:29,191
I paid for Walter Winchell's
summer home, for christssake.

930
00:36:29,275 --> 00:36:30,776
Fans don't want to see this.

931
00:36:30,860 --> 00:36:33,278
They want the hausfrau from Queens.

932
00:36:33,362 --> 00:36:35,906
Ooh. Macaroons.

933
00:36:35,990 --> 00:36:39,326
[LAUGHS] You are so refreshing.

934
00:36:39,410 --> 00:36:41,870
-Hmm?
-Eating a macaroon like that.

935
00:36:41,954 --> 00:36:43,539
Oh, am I eating it wrong?

936
00:36:43,623 --> 00:36:45,708
No, no, no. You're eating it.

937
00:36:45,792 --> 00:36:47,334
[SOPHIE CHUCKLES]

938
00:36:47,418 --> 00:36:49,712
Leave the wedge, please.

939
00:37:02,724 --> 00:37:05,226
My goodness, you're so pretty.

940
00:37:05,310 --> 00:37:08,021
Why comedy? Can't you sing?

941
00:37:08,105 --> 00:37:11,315
Nope. The comedy thing…
I… I just fell into it.

942
00:37:11,399 --> 00:37:12,817
Mm, me, too.

943
00:37:12,901 --> 00:37:14,861
-I went to Yale Drama School.
-You're kidding.

944
00:37:14,945 --> 00:37:17,321
Yes, I wanted to be
the next Laurette Taylor.

945
00:37:17,405 --> 00:37:19,365
Then I graduated, and I starved,

946
00:37:19,449 --> 00:37:22,869
so I started doing this character…
Sophie from Queens.

947
00:37:22,953 --> 00:37:24,871
And look what it paid for.

948
00:37:24,955 --> 00:37:26,330
Dawes?

949
00:37:26,414 --> 00:37:29,332
-Yes, ma'am?
-Isn't that marvelous?

950
00:37:29,416 --> 00:37:32,836
-Uh…
-So tell me

951
00:37:32,920 --> 00:37:35,255
what is your gimmick?

952
00:37:35,339 --> 00:37:37,549
-My…
-Your persona.

953
00:37:37,633 --> 00:37:39,176
-Your Sophie.
-Oh.

954
00:37:39,260 --> 00:37:41,720
I don't have a persona. I'm just me.

955
00:37:41,804 --> 00:37:44,306
Oh, no, no, no, that will not work.

956
00:37:44,390 --> 00:37:46,641
-It won't?
-No. No one wants that.

957
00:37:46,725 --> 00:37:48,143
I… I've been doing okay.

958
00:37:48,227 --> 00:37:49,728
Downtown.

959
00:37:49,812 --> 00:37:51,980
Honey, you give a
downtowner a swig of gin,

960
00:37:52,064 --> 00:37:54,066
and he'll laugh at a sponge.

961
00:37:54,150 --> 00:37:56,985
The mainstreamers,
the people from Pacoima,

962
00:37:57,069 --> 00:38:00,571
the people who buy the
dish soap and the dog food,

963
00:38:00,655 --> 00:38:05,493
who pay for the Modigliani's…
they want a character.

964
00:38:05,577 --> 00:38:07,787
But… Bob Hope doesn't have a character.

965
00:38:07,871 --> 00:38:09,622
Lenny Bruce doesn't have a character.

966
00:38:09,706 --> 00:38:12,416
They have dicks. Do you have a dick?

967
00:38:12,500 --> 00:38:14,210
Not last time I checked.

968
00:38:14,294 --> 00:38:16,587
Darling, look at you.

969
00:38:16,671 --> 00:38:19,548
I mean, really…
men don't want to laugh at you.

970
00:38:19,632 --> 00:38:21,092
They want to fuck you.

971
00:38:21,176 --> 00:38:23,135
You can't go up there and be a woman.

972
00:38:23,219 --> 00:38:25,054
You've got to be a thing.

973
00:38:25,138 --> 00:38:26,597
You want to get ahead in comedy?

974
00:38:26,681 --> 00:38:28,766
Cover up that hole.

975
00:38:28,850 --> 00:38:30,975
Another macaroon, miss?

976
00:38:31,059 --> 00:38:32,560
No, thank you, Dawes.

977
00:38:32,644 --> 00:38:35,063
You're learning.

978
00:38:36,565 --> 00:38:40,110
So… you got the grand tour?

979
00:38:40,194 --> 00:38:41,986
My feet hurt, we walked so much.

980
00:38:42,070 --> 00:38:43,738
[LAUGHS] I love that you love kitchens.

981
00:38:43,822 --> 00:38:45,406
-I do.
-Mm.

982
00:38:45,490 --> 00:38:47,534
You should visit yours sometime.
It misses you.

983
00:38:47,618 --> 00:38:49,410
Oh, and you have macaroons to take home.

984
00:38:49,494 --> 00:38:50,829
This was very nice.

985
00:38:50,913 --> 00:38:52,831
-Mm.
-Thank you, Sophie.

986
00:38:52,915 --> 00:38:54,874
I have a feeling we're
going to be seeing a lot

987
00:38:54,958 --> 00:38:56,292
of each other in the future.

988
00:38:56,376 --> 00:38:57,836
I hope so.

989
00:38:57,920 --> 00:38:59,796
Well, good luck tomorrow night.

990
00:38:59,880 --> 00:39:02,005
Say hello to Harry and make him laugh.

991
00:39:02,089 --> 00:39:03,674
-I will do my best.
-Mm.

992
00:39:03,758 --> 00:39:05,175
Your coat, miss.

993
00:39:05,259 --> 00:39:07,094
What is that?

994
00:39:07,178 --> 00:39:08,720
That is my coat.

995
00:39:08,804 --> 00:39:11,056
That flimsy thing? It's freezing out.

996
00:39:11,140 --> 00:39:14,309
Uh-uh. Jenkins?

997
00:39:14,393 --> 00:39:17,897
A fat suit is very warm, by the way.

998
00:39:22,068 --> 00:39:24,820
